crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_raw: alert tcp any any -> any $HTTP_PORTS ( msg:"POLICY-OTHER HTTP request by IPv4 address attempt"; flow:to_server,established; http_header; content:"Host:",fast_pattern,nocase; pcre:"/^Host\x3a\s*(?:(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9]?[0-9])\.){3}(?:25[0-5]|2[0-4][0-9]|[01]?[0-9]?[0-9])\s*:?\s*\d*\s*$/ims"; service:http; reference:url,www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec15.html; classtype:policy-violation; sid:50447; rev:1; )

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary exhibits behaviors consistent with a malicious loader or Trojan. It employs a multi-stage execution flow where it decrypts an embedded payload using an XOR loop in function sub_401595, allocates memory via VirtualAlloc, and modifies memory protections to PAGE_EXECUTE_READ using VirtualProtect before executing the code via CreateThread. The sample also manually resolves critical APIs (GetModuleHandleA and GetProcAddress) within the decrypted buffer to bypass standard IAT-based detection. Furthermore, it establishes Inter-Process Communication (IPC) using a named pipe (e.g., \\.\pipe\p-i-p-e\MSSE-%d-server), a common technique for stealthy internal communication or credential pivoting.
